    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The narrative of \"straight-line progress\" is a simplification, as the movement faced intense, violent pushback from segregationist forces. While nonviolence was central, there were significant, equally important strains of activism, including the Black Power movement. This shift emphasized self-defense, racial pride, and community empowerment, moving beyond the purely integrationist goals of earlier leaders. These different approaches represented a necessary evolution in the fight for true equality.",
